AGI -&nbsp; Suffocated by the machine of repression at home, fragmented and submerged abroad, the Russian opposition arrives strongly weakened on the first anniversary of the death of its leader Aleksei Navalny>, with the war in Ukraine that is about to enter the fourth year.
&nbsp;
After the large-scale invasion of 24 February 2022, the repression of the Kremlin increased > and is making survival almost impossible for independent political voices. As a result, the most important figures of the opposition now live abroad and have practically no tools to effectively affect the situation within Russia, where for three years we live in conditions of military censorship.
<br> La<a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-02-16/navalny-morto-in-carcere-25323769/"> death of Navalny on 16 February last year</a>, in a prison of maximum security in circumstances still unclear, left - together with a wave of attacks both physical and verbal
&nbsp;
Even among young people, who were the hard-foil of support in Navalny, the public inheritance of the opposition leader has vanished rapidly in this last year. The anti-corruption lawyer and activist who had challenged Vladimir Putin directly for the Kremlin hoped that the young people of the great cities and pro-Western would help him in the mission of disposing the president.
<br But on the streets of Moscow, today, the name Navalny arouses only indifference or fear. >
"We are afraid to talk about this person," said Victoria, 24 years old, interviewed by the agency Afp. Moscow banned all forms of public dissent > during the offensive in Ukraine, intensified the repression of the organization of Navalny, the Anti-corruption Fund (Fbk), its collaborators and its relatives even after his death.
<br> Three of his lawyers were sentenced to prison, journalists who followed his court hearings were arrested and his wife Yulia Navalnaya was added to a black list of "terrorists and extremists". Anyone who mentions Navalny or Fbk, without specifying that they were declared "extremists", in Russia is subject to fines or up to four years in prison.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<br> Finally, while opposition leaders seek to work with European and American chancellors, > pressure on the sanctions lists, discussing Russia's future in the European Parliament or supporting Russian refugees in the United States, anti-Putin resistance still lacks a universally recognized structure > that can act as a true representative body for Russian diaspora, defend its rights and build a common platform with a minimal political proposal
